# CODE HYGIENE

> This file defines the code quality standards for the City Asset Registry System.
> These rules apply to all contributors — human developers and AI agents alike.
> "It works" is not enough. Code must also be readable, consistent, and maintainable.

---

## Why This Matters

This system manages government assets and is subject to audit. The code itself is subject to review — by other developers, by AI agents picking up work mid-project, and potentially by auditors inspecting how data is handled. Sloppy code in a compliance system creates:

- Security vulnerabilities that are hard to spot
- Bugs that are hard to reproduce and trace
- Handoff problems when a developer or AI agent needs to continue work
- Distrust in the system's outputs

Clean code is not perfectionism — it is professional accountability.

---

## Automated Enforcement

Most hygiene rules in this file are automatically enforced by `vp check`.

```bash
vp check         # Runs Oxfmt (format) + Oxlint (lint) + tsgolint (type-check)
vp check --fix   # Auto-fixes formatting and autofixable lint errors
```

**Never manually adjust spacing, indentation, semicolons, or trailing commas.** Let the formatter handle it. If you find yourself fighting the formatter, stop and understand why — the formatter is almost always right.

`vp check` must pass with zero errors before any commit. If it does not pass, the commit does not happen.

