## TypeScript

### Strict mode is always on

`tsconfig.json` has `"strict": true` and it is never disabled. This enables:
- `strictNullChecks` — no implicit `null` or `undefined`
- `noImplicitAny` — no untyped values
- `strictFunctionTypes` — correct function parameter variance
- `strictPropertyInitialization` — all class properties must be initialized

### No `any`

`any` disables TypeScript entirely for that value. It is prohibited.

```ts
// ❌ Wrong
function processAsset(data: any) { ... }

// ✅ Correct — use unknown and narrow it
function processAsset(data: unknown) {
  if (typeof data !== 'object' || data === null) throw new Error('Invalid input')
  // Now narrow further as needed
}

// ✅ Correct — define the actual type
function processAsset(data: InsertAsset) { ... }
```

**Exception:** Third-party library internals that leak `any`. In those cases, use type assertions with a comment explaining why.

### No `@ts-ignore` or `@ts-expect-error` without explanation

```ts
// ❌ Wrong — silent suppression, no explanation
// @ts-ignore
someFunction(badArg)

// ✅ Acceptable — only if truly unavoidable, with explanation
// @ts-expect-error: drizzle-typebox returns a union type that narrows
// incorrectly in this context. Tracked in issue #123.
const schema = createInsertSchema(assets)
```

If you are reaching for `@ts-ignore`, stop and reconsider the approach. There is almost always a proper solution.

### Explicit return types on all exported functions

```ts
// ❌ Wrong — implicit return type
export function getAssetById(id: string) {
  return db.query.assets.findFirst({ where: eq(assets.id, id) })
}

// ✅ Correct — explicit return type
export async function getAssetById(id: string): Promise<Asset | undefined> {
  return db.query.assets.findFirst({ where: eq(assets.id, id) })
}
```

Internal/private helper functions may use inferred return types when the type is obvious.

### `type` vs `interface`

- Prefer `type` for object shapes, unions, and aliases
- Use `interface` only when you need declaration merging or extending (rare in this project)

```ts
// ✅ Preferred
type Asset = {
  id: string
  assetName: string
  departmentId: string
}

// ✅ Also fine when extending is actually needed
interface PaginatedResponse<T> {
  data: T[]
  meta: PaginationMeta
}
```

### No implicit `undefined` in function parameters

```ts
// ❌ Wrong — callers can omit this and get undefined silently
function createAsset(name: string, departmentId?: string) { ... }

// ✅ Correct — be explicit about whether the parameter is required
function createAsset(name: string, departmentId: string): Promise<Asset> { ... }

// ✅ Also correct — optional is fine when it truly is optional, but type it explicitly
function searchAssets(query: string, limit: number = 25): Promise<Asset[]> { ... }
```

